00:00:58.520 --> 00:01:00.160
The first question I have

00:01:00.160 --> 00:01:05.310
for you both is what inspired
the program selections today?

00:01:07.080 --> 00:01:11.050
&gt;&gt; Alban Gerhardt: Well, actually
the program was designed for Europe

00:01:11.050 --> 00:01:18.470
because we American pianist
and German cellist could do

00:01:18.470 --> 00:01:19.770
[ inaudible ]

00:01:19.770 --> 00:01:21.070
program.

00:01:21.070 --> 00:01:27.820
So the original program
was actually instead

00:01:27.820 --> 00:01:33.350
of the Britten it was the
Villa-Lobos sonata but actually

00:01:33.350 --> 00:01:37.960
after looking, it looked very
good on paper, but when we started

00:01:37.960 --> 00:01:41.300
or when I started looking
closer, I really didn't thought,

00:01:41.300 --> 00:01:43.110
think it fit as well
to the other pieces.

00:01:43.110 --> 00:01:44.410
So we kicked out the Villa-Lobos

00:01:44.410 --> 00:01:45.900
since we had played the Britten
before, and we loved it so much,

00:01:45.900 --> 00:01:48.040 position:56%
I think it's one of the best pieces
of German music in the 20th century.

00:01:48.040 --> 00:01:50.900
So we threw it in, and
Britten spoke English.

00:01:50.900 --> 00:01:58.810
So at some point America was
England and whatever, so.

00:01:58.810 --> 00:02:00.210
But.

00:02:00.210 --> 00:02:01.990
&gt;&gt; Anne-Marie McDermott: Well, no,
I was just going to add, you know,

00:02:01.990 --> 00:02:04.590
it's always fun putting
programs together.

00:02:04.590 --> 00:02:06.400
