00:24:57.150 --> 00:25:00.510
but you should not listen, you
should not take his Britten

00:25:00.510 --> 00:25:03.400
of playing as an example
of how it should be done.

00:25:03.400 --> 00:25:06.310
Because I'm sure Britten
didn't tell him anything.

00:25:06.310 --> 00:25:09.870
This little humming story,
that's cute, but he, and, like,

00:25:09.870 --> 00:25:11.500
with the cello symphony,

00:25:11.500 --> 00:25:17.050 position:56%
he's ignoring strongly what Britten
wrote, and actually it doesn't work.

00:25:17.050 --> 00:25:20.890
I mean, I don't, I, 95 percent of
the things Rostropovich recorded

00:25:20.890 --> 00:25:24.110
and played, I love,
but his Britten -- eh.

00:25:24.110 --> 00:25:25.410
It's too Russian.

00:25:25.410 --> 00:25:30.070
He doesn't get the British
sense of humor that, yeah.

00:25:30.070 --> 00:25:34.170
I don't know, and so I can't
meet the part of the story

00:25:34.170 --> 00:25:37.640
that Britten dared to tell
Rostropovich what, yes.

00:25:37.640 --> 00:25:42.050
But then later because Rostropovich
understood [inaudible] down here,

00:25:42.050 --> 00:25:45.600
but, again, to take it as an
example would be quite bad

00:25:45.600 --> 00:25:47.460
because just the fact
that Rostropovich worked

00:25:47.460 --> 00:25:49.470
with just the [inaudible]
does not mean

00:25:49.470 --> 00:25:53.040
that Rostropovich was doing
what Shostakovich wanted.

00:25:53.040 --> 00:25:58.750
Shostakovich was spineless
little paranoid person,

00:25:58.750 --> 00:26:01.580
and he would not stand up and tell
this great charismatic person how

00:26:01.580 --> 00:26:02.880
to play the piece.

00:26:02.880 --> 00:26:06.310
He was happy that such a fantastic
cellist was taking his stuff on.

00:26:06.310 --> 00:26:09.040
I mean, I played pieces
by composers.

00:26:09.040 --> 00:26:14.820
They hardly ever tell you what to
do unless you ask, but I never ask.

00:26:18.640 --> 00:26:19.940
&gt;&gt; Nicholas A. Brown: Great.

00:26:19.940 --> 00:26:21.870
&gt;&gt; Alban Gerhardt: But
