00:26:37.310 --> 00:26:40.250
Britten wrote something on it.

00:26:40.250 --> 00:26:42.220
Britten and Rostropovich
were playing a program here.

00:26:42.220 --> 00:26:43.950
Do you know the story?

00:26:43.950 --> 00:26:47.080
And they played somewhere in
North England forever to stay

00:26:47.080 --> 00:26:51.270
with a friend of Britten's, duke,

00:26:51.270 --> 00:26:54.390
and Shostakovich was
completely excited

00:26:54.390 --> 00:26:58.370
because we don't have
dukes in Russia anymore.

00:26:58.370 --> 00:27:01.970
So I need to practice
my bow for the duke.

00:27:01.970 --> 00:27:09.860
So at every little stop they took
to go to the bathroom or to eat,

00:27:09.860 --> 00:27:12.100
Rostropovich was taking
a bow, and Britten was,

00:27:12.100 --> 00:27:13.400
he told it for the first time.

00:27:13.400 --> 00:27:15.430
No, don't have to do anything.

00:27:15.430 --> 00:27:16.730
We're in England.

00:27:16.730 --> 00:27:18.030
So, no, no, I have to.

00:27:18.030 --> 00:27:19.330
You don't understand.

00:27:19.330 --> 00:27:20.730
Britten got more and
more embarrassed,

00:27:20.730 --> 00:27:22.410
the bigger the bows became.

00:27:22.410 --> 00:27:26.100
At some point, Britten
said, OK, anything you want.

00:27:26.100 --> 00:27:29.320
Just don't bow, and
Rostropovich says OK.

00:27:29.320 --> 00:27:30.870
Write me something for cello.

00:27:30.870 --> 00:27:32.780
OK, OK. No, no, no.

00:27:32.780 --> 00:27:37.000
You have to write it now,
and then Britten wrote "Me,

00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:40.560
Benjamin Britten...I confirmed
that I will write something

00:27:40.560 --> 00:27:42.230
for Mstislav Rostropovich.

00:27:42.230 --> 00:27:45.770
And this thing where he
wrote it on the [inaudible]

00:27:45.770 --> 00:27:48.140
but maybe now it's somewhere else.

00:27:48.140 --> 00:27:55.270 position:56%
